# Summary of the new feature/enhancement

If you want to allow your cmdlet to input argument as from pipeline as from input array or from remaining arguments then you are in troubles.

```PowerShell
function Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet {
    [cmdletbinding()]
    param(
        [Parameter(Position = 0, ValueFromRemainingArguments, ValueFromPipeline)]
        $MyArgs) # Do not specify a type!

    begin {
        [System.Collections.Generic.List[string]]$inputArgs = @()
    }
    process {
        if ($null -ne $MyArgs) {
            if ($MyArgs -is [string]) {
                $inputArgs.Add($MyArgs)
            }
            elseif ($MyArgs -is [System.Collections.IEnumerable]) {
                # PowerShell <= 5.1 bug workaround
                if ($PSVersionTable.PSVersion -lt "6.0" `
                        -and $MyArgs -is [System.Collections.Generic.List[object]] `
                        -and $MyArgs.Count -eq 1 `
                        -and $MyArgs[0] -is [System.Collections.IEnumerable]) {
                    $MyArgs = $MyArgs[0]
                }

                $MyArgs | % {
                    $inputArgs.Add($_)
                }
            }
            else {
                $inputArgs.Add($MyArgs)
            }
        }
    }
    end {
        Write-Host "-------- Args -------"
        $inputArgs | % { Write-Host $_ }
    }
}

# Usage tests:
Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet # No args
Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet "SingleArg"
Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet "Multi" "Args"
@("Pile", "line") | Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet
$null | Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet
[System.Management.Automation.Internal.AutomationNull]::Value | Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet
# Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet [System.Management.Automation.Internal.AutomationNull]::Value It's not supported
@($null, "123") | Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet
@("", "123") | Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet
Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet "123" ""

Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet @("Args", "Array")
```
Output:
```
-------- Args -------
-------- Args -------
SingleArg
-------- Args -------
Multi
Args
-------- Args -------
Pile
line
-------- Args -------
-------- Args -------
-------- Args -------
123
-------- Args -------

123
-------- Args -------
123

-------- Args -------
Args
Array
```

The provided code behaves similar in both PS Core and Windows PowerShell.

Please make all these tricks just like language construct
```PowerShell
function Read-FancyInputArgumentsLogoCmdlet {
    [cmdletbinding()]
    param(
        [Parameter(ValuesFromEverywhere)]
        [string]$MyArg)
    begin {
        [System.Collections.Generic.List[string]]$inputArgs = @()
    }
    process {
        $inputArgs.Add($MyArg)
    }
    end {
        Write-Host "-------- Args -------"
        $inputArgs | % { Write-Host $_ }
    }
}
```

# Summary of the new feature/enhancement

I had some code working locally on a Windows laptop in Powershell 5, which used Net.WebRequest to get the Certificate returned by a server, so as to validate its ownership.

Tried to use the code in PowerShell 6, and/or in Azure Functions (which also use PS6), and was unable to do so - ServicePoint.Certificate was always $null, no matter what site I tried.

I see you've done some work adding -SkipCertificateCheck, and are working on adding custom certificate validation functionality - but all I really need is to see what certificate is provided by the web server. Ideally without performing the entire request - I currently use a HEAD Method, but I'm aware that might have issues, too.

# Proposed technical implementation details (optional)

Current code (PS5):
$wr1 = [Net.HttpWebRequest]::Create('https://www.github.com')
$wr1.Method = 'HEAD'
$ignore = $wr1.GetResponse()
if ($wr1.ServicePoint -ne $null)
{
  if ($wr1.ServicePoint.Certificate -ne $null) {
    Write-Host "The certificate is $($wr1.ServicePoint.Certificate.Subject)"
  } else {
    Write-Host "The certificate is null - can't get the subject."
  }
} else {
  Write-Host "The service point is null, can't get the certificate."
}

Ideal target code, something like:

$wr1 = Invoke-WebRequest 'https://www.github.com' -SkipCertificateCheck -SkipHeaderValidation -Method 'Head'
Write-Host "Certificate subject is $($wr1.Certificate.Subject)"

# Summary of the new feature/enhancement

Currently registering a PSTypeConverter that converts to string doesn't do anything.
Any defined functionality is ignored for `value.ToString()`.

An example to try out:

```csharp
using System;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.IO;
using System.Management.Automation;

[TypeConverter]
public class DirectoryInfoTypeConverter : PSTypeConverter
{
    public override bool CanConvertFrom(object source, Type type)
    {
        return source.GetType() == typeof(DirectoryInfo)
            && type == typeof(string);
    }

    public override object ConvertFrom(object source, Type type, IFormatProvider fp, bool ignoreCase)
    {
        return "moo";
    }

    public override bool CanConvertTo(object source, Type type)
    {
        return source.GetType() == typeof(DirectoryInfo)
            && type == typeof(string);
    }

    public override object ConvertTo(object source, Type type, IFormatProvider fp, bool ignoreCase)
    {
        return "moo";
    }
}
```

```powershell
Update-TypeData -TypeConverter DirectoryInfoTypeConverter -TypeName System.IO.DirectoryInfo

(gi .) -as [string]
```

Compare this to if you change the original converter to:

```csharp
[TypeConverter]
public class DirectoryInfoTypeConverter : PSTypeConverter
{
    public override bool CanConvertFrom(object source, Type type)
    {
        return source.GetType() == typeof(DirectoryInfo)
            && type == typeof(int);
    }

    public override object ConvertFrom(object source, Type type, IFormatProvider fp, bool ignoreCase)
    {
        return 33;
    }

    public override bool CanConvertTo(object source, Type type)
    {
        return source.GetType() == typeof(DirectoryInfo)
            && type == typeof(int);
    }

    public override object ConvertTo(object source, Type type, IFormatProvider fp, bool ignoreCase)
    {
        return 12;
    }
}
```

This is actually already [a uservoice issue](https://windowsserver.uservoice.com/forums/301869-powershell/suggestions/16972927-custom-pstypeconverter-cannot-be-used-to-convert-o).

# Proposed technical implementation details (optional)

We should discuss how this code:

https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/blob/f5e3de036e84f37820eb1dac635c337f8fc17718/src/System.Management.Automation/engine/LanguagePrimitives.cs#L5620-L5652

could be changed. Clearly PowerShell currently has a set of types where the language type conversion takes precedence, and it's not clear why that's not configurable. Inserting a type converter lookup as the first call would not break most cases, but could break some things.

Also that `if`/`else` cascade needs a serious refactor...
